The octagonal type is thought to reflect ideological influences, including {{ill|Buddhist cosmology|ja|仏教宇宙論|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Buddhist cosmology|qq=}}, where the octagon symbolizes repose for the soul, as well as {{ill|Chinese cosmology|ja|中国思想|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chinese cosmology|qq=}}, representing imperial rites and the order of the universe. While this tomb type was predominantly used for {{ill|Imperial mausoleums|ja|天皇陵|1=Japanese imperial tombs|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial mausoleums|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese imperial tombs|qq=}} in western Japan, it is rare in eastern Japan, with examples including the {{ill|Inarizuka Kofun|ja|稲荷塚古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inarizuka Kofun|qq=}} in {{ill|Tama City|ja|多摩市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tama City|qq=}}, Tokyo, and the {{ill|Isezuka Kofun|ja|伊勢塚古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Isezuka Kofun|qq=}} in {{ill|Fujioka|ja|藤岡市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujioka|qq=}}, Gunma Prefecture.

During the tumulus restoration in 1994, traditional wooden winches, locally known as "kagurasan," were used instead of modern heavy machinery.

