'''Kyozuka Kofun''' (経塚古墳) is an {{ill|Octagonal Kofun|ja|八角墳|1=Octagonal Kofun|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Octagonal Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Octagonal Kofun|qq=}} located in [[:en:Fuefuki|Fuefuki, Yamanashi]], [[:en:Yamanashi Prefecture|Yamanashi Prefecture]], Japan. It is Historic Site1 as a Yamanashi Prefectural Historic Site.<ref>[https://www.pref.yamanashi.jp/bunka/maibun/yamanashinobunkazai_shiseki003.html#SHI0032 Kyozuka Kofun] - Yamanashi Prefectural Website</ref>

== Overview ==

[[File:Kyozuka Kofun (Fuefuki), sekishitsu.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Interior of the stone chamber}}]]
Located in the eastern part of the [[Kōfu Basin]] on the alluvial fan of the [[:en:Jinchuan|Kanagawa River]], Kyozuka Kofun lies at an elevation of 348 meters. The surrounding area contains the remnants of the {{ill|Kokubu Kofun Cluster|ja|国分古墳群|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokubu Kofun Cluster|qq=}}, dating from the late Kofun period to the terminal Kofun period, as well as the sites of the [[Kai Kokubunji|Kai Provincial Temple]] and {{ill|Kai Provincial Nunnery|ja|甲斐国分尼寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kai Provincial Nunnery|qq=}} from the subsequent Nara period.

Previously believed to be a small circular tomb from the 6th to 7th century, the kofun was reclassified as an octagonal tumulus during excavations conducted in [[1994]] (Heisei 6) by the {{ill|Yamanashi Prefectural Board of Education|ja|山梨県教育委員会|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamanashi Prefectural Board of Education|qq=}}. This makes it one of only nine such examples nationwide and the third known in eastern Japan.

The excavation revealed a {{ill|yokoana-shiki sekishitsu|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/yokoana-shiki sekishitsu|13=User:Immanuelle/Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=}} (horizontal stone chamber), which was fully dismantled and restored. Few burial goods were recovered, with the only notable find being an iron axe from the tumulus's construction period. Additional items include {{ill|Kai-style pottery|ja|甲斐型土器|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kai-style pottery|qq=}} and human remains, which are believed to be secondary deposits.

The tumulus measures 12.5 meters in diameter and 2.2 meters in height. Based on the chamber's structure and the burial goods, it is dated to the early 7th century. burial goods from the kofun are preserved at the {{ill|Yamanashi Prefectural Center for Archaeological burial goods|ja|山梨県埋蔵文化センター|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamanashi Prefectural Center for Archaeological burial goods|qq=}}, and the site has been incorporated into the {{ill|Kanegawa-no-Mori Forest Park|ja|森林公園金川の森|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanegawa-no-Mori Forest Park|qq=}}.

The octagonal type is thought to reflect ideological influences, including {{ill|Buddhist cosmology|ja|仏教宇宙論|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Buddhist cosmology|qq=}}, where the octagon symbolizes repose for the soul, as well as {{ill|Chinese cosmology|ja|中国思想|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chinese cosmology|qq=}}, representing imperial rites and the order of the universe. While this tomb type was predominantly used for [[:en:Japanese imperial tombs|Japanese imperial tombs]] in western Japan, it is rare in eastern Japan, with examples including the {{ill|Inarizuka Kofun|ja|稲荷塚古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inarizuka Kofun|qq=}} in [[:en:Tama, Tokyo|Tama City]], Tokyo, and the {{ill|Isezuka Kofun|ja|伊勢塚古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Isezuka Kofun|qq=}} in [[:en:Fujioka, Gunma|Fujioka]], Gunma Prefecture.

During the tumulus restoration in 1994, traditional wooden winches, locally known as "kagurasan," were used instead of modern heavy machinery.

== Historic Site ==
=== Yamanashi Prefectural Historic Site ===
* '''Kyozuka Kofun''' - Designated on November 7, 1994.

